                  <handDesc>
                     <!--ACHTUNG! first HandNote comes from writing system in Ethiospare. the others are one for each CHANGE OF HAND-->
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Hand a: fine and careful; hand b: mediocre</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red (vivid scarlet)</seg>
                        <persName role="scribe" ref="PRS00000">Gabra Māryām</persName>According to
                        the colophon, the scribe who produced the Ms. is Gabra Māryām (hand a). His
                        name is also mentioned in the supplication formulas up to <locus target="#53va">53va</locus>.<date>First half of the 19th century</date>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Nomina sacra; the name of the scribe; a few groups
                           of lines (alternating with black lines) on the incipit page of Text I;
                           the incipit and number of the miracles; the incipit of sections of
                           miracles 34 and 48; elements of the punctuation signs; elements of
                           Ethiopic numerals.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">Hand a: <locus from="3ra" to="79ra">3ra-79ra</locus> l.7: the letters are slightly right-sloping, tall and
                        slim.
                        <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic"> In <locus from="59ra" to="79ra">59ra-79ra</locus> the handwriting slightly changes: the letters are
                        bigger in size, occasionally broadly spaced (<locus target="#71r">71r</locus>, 74v).
                        <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic"> Hand b: <locus target="#79ra">79ra</locus> l.5-118vb: the letters are right-sloping, wide and angular,
                        the individual strokes forming the letter are frequently not
                        joined.<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                  </handDesc>
